w 2 more parallel lines.";i:19;s:31:"Connect the edges of each V to.";i:20;s:34:"Chair conformation you start with.";i:21;s:39:"Drawing the Chair Flipped Conformation.";i:22;s:84:"To draw the chair flip conformation you have to redraw the ring as its mirror image.";i:23;s:77:"This will represent the new conformation as it should look if the ring flips.";i:24;s:53:"Carbon 1 which was an up carbon is now a down carbon.";i:25;s:31:"Carbon 4 which was down is now.";i:26;s:349:"In the previous two posts we have talked about drawing the ring-flip of chair conformations and the A value 13-diaxial interactionsAnd we learned that for a given cyclohexane the axial conformer is less stable than the corresponding equatorial conformerFor example the energy difference of the axial and equatorial isopropyl cyclohexane is 92 kJmol.";i:27;s:144:"This video demonstrates how to perform a chair flip and how to determine which conformation of a substituted cyclohexane is the more stable one.";i:28;s:72:"Drawing Conformers of Cyclohexanes and Conformational Analysis MAHACP 4.";i:29;s:198:"Using the numbering scheme in the original structure shown in step 1 and the numbering scheme in the chair conformation templates drawn in step 3 fill in the substituents on the chair conformations.";i:30;s:58:"Use the guidelines below place substituents in the proper.";i:31;s:122:"This organic chemistry video tutorial provides a basic introduction into ring flips of the cyclohexane chair conformation.";i:32;s:72:"It explains how to sketch the chair conformation of cyclohexane and how.";i:33;s:69:"A red oak traditional Morris chair was an awesome find and Katey and.";i:34;s:111:"To begin start by drawing two lines that are parallel to each other but not perfectly horizontal as shown here.";i:35;s:76:"Next add a downward-pointing V tip to one end this is the tail of the chair.";i:36;s:84:"Finally add an upward-pointing V tip to the other end this is the nose of the chair.";i:37;s:68:"The steps involved i